SIMPLE: engine
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Engine
<hw>En"gine</hw> <pr>(⟦ecr⟧n"j⟦icr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>engin</ets> skill, machine, engine, L. <ets>ingenium</ets> natural
capacity, invention; <ets>in</ets> in + the root of <ets>gignere</ets>
to produce. See <er>Genius</er>, and cf. <er>Ingenious</er>,
<er>Gin</er> a snare.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <note>(Pronounced, in this
sense, <pr>⟦ecr⟧n*j⟦emac⟧n"</pr>.)</note> <def>Natural capacity;
ability; skill.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A man hath sapiences three,⟦br⟧
Memory, <qex>engine</qex>, and intellect also.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Anything used to effect a purpose; any device or
contrivance; a machine; an agent.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You see the ways the fisherman doth take⟦br⟧
To catch the fish; what <qex>engines</qex> doth he make?</q>
<rj><qau>Bunyan.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their promises, enticements, oaths, tokens, and all these
<qex>engines</qex> of lust.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Any instrument by which any effect is produced;
especially, an instrument or machine of war or torture.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Terrible <xex>engines</xex> of death.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sir W.
Raleigh.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>A compound machine by which any
physical power is applied to produce a given physical effect.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Engine driver</b></col>, <cd>one who manages an engine;
specifically, the engineer of a locomotive.</cd> -- <col><b>Engine
lathe</b></col>. <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Lathe</er>.</cd>
-- <col><b>Engine tool</b></col>, <cd>a machine tool.</cd> <au>J.
Whitworth.</au> -- <col><b>Engine turning</b></col> <fld>(Fine
Arts)</fld>, <cd>a method of ornamentation by means of a rose
engine.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The term <xex>engine</xex> is more commonly applied to
massive machines, or to those giving power, or which produce some
difficult result. Engines, as motors, are distinguished according to the
source of power, as <xex>steam engine</xex>, <xex>air engine</xex>,
<xex>electro-magnetic engine</xex>; or the purpose on account of which
the power is applied, as <xex>fire engine</xex>, <xex>pumping
engine</xex>, <xex>locomotive engine</xex>; or some peculiarity of
construction or operation, as <xex>single-acting</xex> or
<xex>double-acting engine</xex>, <xex>high-pressure</xex> or
<xex>low-pressure engine</xex>, <xex>condensing engine</xex>,
etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Engine</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Engine
<hw>En"gine</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To assault with an
engine.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>engine</qex> and batter our walls.</q> <rj><qau>T.
Adams.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To equip with an engine; -- said especially of steam
vessels; <as>as, vessels are often built by one firm and
<ex>engined</ex> by another</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>(Pronounced, in this sense, <?/<?/<?/<?/<?/.) To
rack; to torture.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Engineer</ent>⟦br⟧
